e characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Gwyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan) and Irish: variant of   Gwin   or   Gwynne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwin","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>gwyn</i> ‘fair, white’, also sometimes ‘white-headed; favorite’. This word was widely used as a personal name in the Middle Ages. It may also be a nickname for a person with fair hair or a noticeably pale complexion. See also   Winn  ."]}]},{"name":"Collwyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern: adoption of the Daffyd place name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Collwyn ap Gwyn of Blaen Cuch was born in 0995, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Gwyn ap Rhydderch and Mrs Gwyn ap Rhydderch. He married Mrs Collwyn ap Gwyn of Blaen Cuch before 1030, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"0995–":"0995–Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","0997–Female":"0997–Surnud","1030–1091":"1030–1091","1010–1091":"1010–1091","1035–Male":"1035–Surnud","0965–1030":"0965–1030","–Female":"Surnud","1091":"1091","0997":"0997","099